{{Infobox person |name = Tanaka Shōzō |image = Tanaka Shozo.jpg |caption = Shōzō Tanaka |birth_date = {{Birth date|1841|12|15}} |birth_place = [[Sano, Tochigi]], Japan |death_date = {{Death date and age|1913|9|4|1841|12|15|df=yes}} |death_place = Sano, Japan |other_names = |known_for = |occupation = Politician, Environmental activist |nationality = {{flag|Japan}} }}
{{nihongo|'''Shōzō Tanaka'''|田中 正造|Tanaka Shōzō||extra=15 December 1841 – 4 September 1913}}<ref name="NDL">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndl.go.jp/portrait/e/datas/290.html|title=Tanaka, Shozo|publisher=National Diet Library, Japan|accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref> was a Japanese politician and social activist, and is considered to be [[Japan]]'s "first conservationist."<ref name="Focus">{{cite web|url=http://www.japanfocus.org/-Robert-Stolz/2331|title=Remake Politics, Not Nature: Tanaka Shozo’s Philosophies of "Poison" and "Flow" and Japan’s Environment|author=Robert Stolz|publisher=The Asia-Pacific Journal|accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref> He is most well known for his defence of the right of workers victims of the [[Ashio Copper Mine#Ashio Copper Mine Incident|Ashio Copper Mine Incident]].
== Life and influence ==
He was born in the village of Konaka in present-day [[Sano, Tochigi|Sano]], [[Tochigi Prefecture]], and was the son of the village [[Village head|headman]]. In 1857, he became headman after his father and served for twelve years.<ref name="Perspectives"/>{{rp|113}} In 1879, he founded the ''Tochigi Shimbun'', a periodical in which he discussed human rights and contemporary issues.<ref name="n">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) |title=田中正造 |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2013-11-08 |year=2013 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Shōzō Tanaka |oclc=153301537 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=August 25, 2007 }}</ref>
Tanaka became a member of the Tochigi Prefectural Assembly in 1880, and its Chairman in 1886.<ref name="NDL"/> In the [[Japanese general election, 1890|general election of 1890]], the first ever held in Japan, he was elected to the [[House of Representatives (Japan)|House of Representatives]] as a member of the [[Rikken Kaishintō]], a liberal political party.<ref name="NDL"/>
Tanaka is best known for his advocacy in connection with the pollution caused by waste from the [[Ashio Copper Mine]].<ref name="Letter">{{cite web|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/anti-nuclear-japanese-lawmaker-attacked-from-all-sides-for-handing-letter-to-emperor-akihito-1.687774|title=Anti-nuclear Japanese lawmaker attacked from all sides for handing letter to Emperor Akihito|author=Mari Yamaguchi|publisher=Associated Press|date=November 7, 2013|accessdate=November 8, 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224125726/http://www.timescolonist.com/anti-nuclear-japanese-lawmaker-attacked-from-all-sides-for-handing-letter-to-emperor-akihito-1.687774|archivedate=February 24, 2014|df=}}</ref> Starting from the mid-1880s, rivers near the mine became highly polluted and in 1890 a large flood carried poisonous wastes from the mine into surrounding areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.unu.edu/unupress/unupbooks/uu35ie/uu35ie04.htm|title=The Ashio Copper mine pollution case: The origins of environmental destruction, Ch. 1, Sec. II|author=Kichiro Shoji and Masuro Sugai|publisher=United Nations University|accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref> Tanaka took the cause to the [[National Diet]], but his efforts to publicise the pollution met with little success.<ref name="Perspectives"/>{{rp|115}} In 1900, villagers in the valley of the [[Watarase River]], downstream from the mine, planned a mass protest in [[Tokyo]], but were rebuffed by government troops and forced to disperse. In 1901, Tanaka resigned from the Diet to deliver an appeal directly to [[Emperor Meiji]].<ref name="Letter"/><ref name="Policy">{{cite book|last=Imura|first=Hidefumi|title=Environmental Policy in Japan|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|page=18|year=2005|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t3_pgPtf-QoC&pg=PA18|accessdate=November 8, 2013|isbn=9781781008249}}</ref> In 1911, the Diet passed the Factory Law, Japan's first law to address industrial pollution.<ref name="Policy"/>
Tanaka was a supporter of local autonomy and the primacy of agriculture.<ref name="Perspectives">{{cite book|last=Wray|first=Harry|last2=Conroy|first2=Hilary|title=Japan Examined: Perspectives on Modern Japanese History|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=1983|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=skbAIYs3kdQC&pg=PA112|accessdate=November 8, 2013|isbn=9780824808396}}</ref>{{rp|112}} He spent the rest of his life developing his own environmental philosophy and encouraging villagers to protest against various construction projects.<ref name="Focus"/> After leaving the Diet he lived in Yanaka village, now a district of the city of Sano, until his death by stomach cancer in 1913.<ref name="n"/> At the time of his pass away, Tanaka was literally penniless as to spend his properties to the past actions; all of his possessions were an unfinished manuscript, a book of the [[New Testament]], handkerchief paper, river [[nori]], 3 pebbles, 3 diaries, a bind copy of the [[Meiji Constitution]] and the [[Gospel of Matthew]] in a cloth bag.<ref>[https://www.city.sano.lg.jp/city-museum/img431.pdf 田中正造展示室資料解説] (pdf). Retrieved on March 24, 2017</ref>
